<DOC><DOCNO> AP880804-0008 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 0748EDT</FILEID><FIRST>b a PM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru 2ndAdd 08-04 0159</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld - Writethru, 2nd Add, a0539,0157</SECOND><HEAD>URGENT</HEAD><HEAD>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla.: the cause.</HEAD><TEXT>   A computer system had taken control of the countdown 31 secondsbefore the planned ignition. When it detected the problem, itautomatically sent a signal to stop the firing sequence.   The shutdown signal came ``just after the go for main enginestart was issued,'' Harris said.   It was another major disappointment for shuttle program managerswho have been grooming Discovery for the first shuttle flight sincethe loss of Challenger and its crew of seven in an explosion 73seconds after liftoff on Jan. 28, 1986.   Harris said that immediately after the shutdown of the system,the launch team remotely began to make the vehicle safe as it saton the pad, its tank loaded with 385,000 gallons of liquid hydrogenand 143,000 gallons of liquid oxygen.   He said preparations were being made to drain the propellantsfrom the fuel tank.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>